message: The first paragraph should simply define the term clearly and neutrally, including how Galton used it since he coined it. Save the controversy and criticism for later in the article since there are defensible and indefensible forms of eugenics.

A small but important edit: Since Galton coined the term, his definition of it should be right in the first paragraph, not buried in a footnote. Moreover, since Galton clearly rejected coercive eugenics and race-based eugenics, the definition should not have coercion or racism built into it (which some editors have tried to do).
changed a comma and dash to a parenthetical
/* History */ Edits intended to improve the clarity of reasoning and cite a scholar on the subject. Deleted a redundant definition of "new eugenics" which is already contained in the first paragraph.
/* Semiotics and history */ most people don't use the word "semiotics" in this context. The word "History" is enough.

Polished the prose without significantly changing the content. Basic idea is to contrast liberal eugenics with older, more illiberal varieties that were often tainted with racist and classist assumptions
/* Your edits to the Intelligence (journal) page */ new section
Removed a part of the article that is nothing but political commentary -- an editorial rather than a neutral description of the journal.
Deleted an erroneous slur.  This was a political opinion, rather than a factual description of the journal.
/* Proposed edits with new sources */ new section

/* History */ Once again, deleted an erroneous sentence added by Greyfell, which falsely claims that liberal eugenics is about population-level traits. It is not, as Nick Agar (who originated the concept) makes crystal clear. The editor who keeps reverting back to this false claim should stop.
Deleted a wildly inaccurate sentence at the end of the first paragraph. The sentence claimed that liberal or
/* Further reading */ added new book to further readings
/* External links */ added references for further reading
Cited authoritative source on definition: the person who invented the term "liberal eugenics"

Undid revision 935183599 by [[Special:Contributions/Aquillion|Aquillion]] ([[User talk:Aquillion|talk]]) These sources mention precisely the points they address: Dan Brock rebuts the view that reproductive rights are unlimited. Savulescu et al argue that deliberate genetic modification can and should preserve genetic diversity. And Buchanan et al argue that natural selection does not select for optimal traits, and that deliberate genetic modification can improve upon nature. These add neutrality
/* Further reading */ Added two book references
added a few references to update the literature cited

Undid revision 938743824 by [[Special:Contributions/PiotruśW|PiotruśW]] ([[User talk:PiotruśW|talk]]). This is incorrect. Go to the talk page and make your case their. You are literally deleting experts in bioethics and replacing them with confusing language that is ideologically biased.

/* History */ deleted the Edwin Black reference for two very important reasons: 1) Black is a journalist, not a historian or a bioethicists, 2) Black is describing the worst excesses of older and more coercive eugenics programs, not liberal eugenics. It biases the page to add Black's critique as if it is authoritative (it's not) or relevant to new eugenics (it's not)
/* Ethics */ added citations and clarified arguments for and against

See talk page. Including definitions by a figure who had nothing to do with "liberal" eugenics is not accurate. The term comes from Agar, not Galton, and it is both false and slanderous to attribute to Agar the view that we should stop those deemed "lesser" or "inferior" from reproducing. He never says this, nor do any of the main advocates of liberal eugenics. See talk page on DEFINITIONS
/* First section of entry is not neutral */
/* First section of entry is not neutral */ new section
/* Split? */ Yes, the articles should be split (they already are), and no, even classical eugenics is not necessarily racist. Classical eugenicists disagreed with one another.
/* CRISPR */ Chiming in on an empirical question: Is CRISPR eugenics? Answer: yes, by definition, if the point is to improve welfare.

Greyfell undid them. This is vandalism on his part.

But surely we should include all mainstream perspectives on this subject, not just left wing activists.
